{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"960"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/960"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.66,0.03,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/960"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84133"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1901"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43049"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to a small rural hospital with a 12-hour history of throbbing headache, worse on the left side. The pain has not responded to paracetamol or ibuprofen. She denies visual disturbances, photophobia, phonophobia, nausea, vomiting, or neurological symptoms. She reports shoulder joint ache, stiffness, and fatigue for several weeks. Her medical history includes hypertension, for which she takes atenolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 150/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Neurological examination is unremarkable with equal and reactive pupils bilaterally. There is mild tenderness on palpation over her scalp, particularly in the temporal region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transfer to regional centre","Temporal artery biopsy","High-dose oral prednisolone","Aspirin","Intravenous methylprednisolone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suspicious for giant cell arteritis (GCA): new-onset temporal headache, scalp tenderness, and symptoms of polymyalgia rheumatica (shoulder pain and stiffness) in a person over 50 years of age. GCA is a medical emergency due to the risk of permanent vision loss. Details regarding treatment for GCA are shown in the table.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-dose oral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E (40-60 mg daily) is the most appropriate initial management for suspected GCA, even before diagnostic confirmation. Treatment should be initiated immediately to prevent irreversible complications, particularly vision loss. In a rural setting, oral prednisolone is readily available and effective as first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to regional centre\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary as the initial management of GCA can be provided at a small rural hospital. The priority is to start corticosteroid therapy without delay, which can be done locally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal artery biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for confirming GCA diagnosis, but treatment should not be delayed while awaiting biopsy. Corticosteroids can be started immediately, and biopsy remains reliable for diagnosis even after 1-2 weeks of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E may be used as an adjunctive therapy in GCA to reduce the risk of ischemic complications, but it is not the appropriate initial management. It would not address the underlying inflammatory process or prevent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients with GCA who present with visual symptoms or vision loss. This patient has no reported visual disturbances, so oral prednisolone is sufficient as initial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations typically show elevated inflammatory markers (ESR and CRP) in GCA, which would support the diagnosis. After initiating treatment, further investigations including temporal artery biopsy and possibly vascular imaging should be arranged to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Giant cell arteritis should be treated immediately with high-dose oral corticosteroids to prevent vision loss.","Clinical features of giant cell arteritis include new-onset temporal headache, scalp tenderness, and constitutional symptoms in patients over 50 years.","Polymyalgia rheumatica frequently coexists with giant cell arteritis, presenting as shoulder and hip girdle pain and stiffness."],"references":["Fraser JA, Weyand CM, Newman NJ, Biousse V. The treatment of giant cell arteritis. Rev Neurol Dis. 2008 Summer;5(3):140-52. PMID: 18838954; PMCID: PMC3014829. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18838954/","Ezeonyeji A, Borg F, Dasgupta B. Delays in recognition and management of giant cell arteritis: results from a retrospective audit. Clinical Rheumatology. 2010;30(2):259-262. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21086005/","Ponte C, Rodrigues AF, O\u0027Neill L, Luqmani RA. Giant cell arteritis: Current treatment and management. World J Clin Cases. 2015 Jun 16;3(6):484-94. doi: 10.12998/wjcc.v3.i6.484. PMID: 26090367; PMCID: PMC4468893. Avaialble from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4468893/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84133"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"960"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18786"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18786"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9ec45348-71a5-430c-87e3-5d0d301e5ef4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9ec45348-71a5-430c-87e3-5d0d301e5ef4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":139}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84133"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T21:53:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T21:54:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"960"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101679"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}}